[normal]People with disabilities 
[normal]are among the poorest of the poor but 
[normal]have not been adequately included in 
[normal]development or 
[normal]the
[normal] 
[normal]MDGs
[normal];
[normal] this must be rectified in any post-2015 development framework which should include clear indicators 
[normal]to measure
[normal] disability inclusion
[normal].
[normal] This is a critical moment for DFID to 
[normal]take a leadership role 
[normal]in 
[normal]champion
[normal]ing
[normal] disability in post-2015 discussions.
[normal]1.
[normal]2
[normal] Mainstreaming people with disabilities into development programmes can be effective if it actively includes people with disabilities in the planning process. 
[normal]A
[normal] conso
[normal]rtium approach, 
[normal]where at least one 
[normal]partner is able to provide expertise in disability
[normal] is an effective model
[normal]. 
[normal]1.3
[normal] 
[normal]Programmes that use a twin-track approach – mainstreaming 
[normal]accompanied by
[normal] disability-
[normal]specific interventions – are 
[normal]particularly
[normal] effective.
[normal]1.4 Disability disaggregated data is nee
[normal]ded at national but also project level
[normal],
[normal] in order to plan appropriately
[normal] and 
[normal]measure inclusion.
[normal] 
[normal]1.5 Disability is not just a medical or physical issue. Strategies must also address the social, psychological and legal issues around disability, including addr
[normal]essing stigma through a combination of individual 
[normal]empowerment
[normal] and community awareness.
[normal]1.6
[normal] Disability strategies, as well as 
[normal]address
[normal]ing the consequences of disability, 
[normal]should consider 
[normal]prevention of
[normal] disability, including the treatment of neglected tropical diseases 
[normal](NTDs) 
[normal]that cause disability, such as leprosy.
[normal] 
[normal]1.8 Inequalities intersect, so people with disabilities can also be marginalised due to gender, caste, ethnicity, location, etc. 
[normal]Mainstreami
[normal]ng is important, with programmes 
[normal]focus
[normal]ing
[normal] on the person rather than 
[normal]just 
[normal]the disability.
[normal]1.8 DFID has begun to recognise the need for disability inclusion but much more needs to be done to ensure the rights of people with disabilities are realised. This sh
[normal]ould include:
