[normal]3.1
[normal] 
[normal]People with disabilities
[normal] comprise some of the 
[normal]world’s 
[normal]most marginalised and vulnerable people
[normal]. A
[normal]ccording to
[normal] 
[normal]the 
[normal]WHO ‘people with 
[normal]disabilities and their families are more likely to experience economic and social disadvantage than those without disability’.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2
[normal] 
[normal]It is not sufficient for development programmes to target the easiest to reach. I
[normal]n order to effectively address poverty
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]DFID-
[normal]supported programmes (including Bilateral and Multilateral Aid) must
[normal] target the poorest-of-the-poor
[normal].
[normal] It
[normal] 
[normal]can
[normal] be argued that without involvement
[normal] of people with disabilities
[normal],
[normal] poverty alleviation measures will not achieve
[normal] 
[normal]full success:
[normal] f
[normal]or ‘
[normal]people with a disability are less likely to attend school, more likely to be unemployed, while 
[normal]h
[normal]ouseholds with a disabled member are more likely to experience material hardship – including food insecurity, poor housing, lack of access to safe water and san
[normal]itation, and 
[normal]inadequate access to health care
[normal]’, affecting a wide range of development indicators.
[normal]  
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.3
[normal] 
[normal]On
[normal] the whole most conv
[normal]entional development programmes
[normal] do not by defaul
[normal]t include people with disabilities
[normal]. This is 
[normal]not
[normal] necessary due to
[normal] their impairment or functional limitation. Inadequate policies, negative attitudes and lack of accessibility oft
[normal]en prohibit their participation
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.4
[normal] 
[normal]The WHO World Report on Disability (2011) calls for inclusion of people with disabilities in mainstream pro
[normal]grammes: ‘
[normal]People with disabilities have ordinary needs – for health and well-being, for economic and social security, to learn and develop skills, and to live in their communities. These needs can and should be met in mainstream programmes and services. Ma
[normal]instreaming not only 
[normal]fulfils
[normal] the human rights of persons with disabili
[normal]ties, it is also more effective’
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.5
[normal] 
[normal]D
[normal]espite there being international recognition that a key factor in preventing the achievement of the Millennium Development Goals (MDGs) is the lack of inclusion of 
[normal]people with disabilities
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]t
[normal]here is currently no DFID polic
[normal]y 
[normal]n
[normal]or strategy on disability. Thu
[normal]s
[normal] there is no obligation for DFID programmes to demonstrate or monitor the inclusion of disabled people
[normal]. Therefore
[normal], disability is not adequately reflected within strategic documents in other areas, such as the Strategic Vision for Women and Girls. Neither is there a requirement that Bilateral 
[normal]n
[normal]or Multilateral Aid is inclusive of people with disabilities.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.6
[normal] 
[normal]Even when di
[normal]sability is said to
[normal] be ‘mainstreamed’ in some DFID-
[normal]supported projects there is evidence
[normal] that this has
[normal] not necessarily 
[normal]been 
[normal]well implemented
[normal]. For example,
[normal] the 
