[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.1
[normal] 
[normal]Disability strategies and programmes 
[normal]must
[normal] recognise that disab
[normal]ility is not just 
[normal]a 
[normal]medical
[normal] condition
[normal]. There are significant s
[normal]ocial impacts of disability
[normal] that must be addressed.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.2
[normal] 
[normal]In many cultures there is shame associated with disability resulting in people with disabilities being hidden away
[normal],
[normal] prevented from engaging in their community and being denied their rights.  People 
[normal]affected by
[normal] leprosy often are scared to admit their condition, or even 
[normal]to 
[normal]seek treatment
[normal],
[normal] because of the stigma and social exclusion that often accompanies diagnosis. Many p
[normal]eople try to hide their disability in order to retain social acceptance. (Annex 2)
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]5.3
[normal] 
[normal]When people experience clawed hands
[normal] due to leprosy
[normal], not only are they unable to grip things, they ar
[normal]e also unable to greet people
[normal]. A simple 
[normal]Indian 
[normal]gesture of greeting 
[normal]‘namaste’
[normal] 
[normal]highlights not only their disability but often triggers a deeply rooted fea
[normal]r of a disease 
[normal]that 
[normal]leads to stigma and discrimination. 
[normal]As a result
[normal], people affected by leprosy often withdraw from social interaction. Barriers to 
[normal]inclusion are not only 
[normal]physical, but also social and psychosocial
[normal];
[normal] 
[normal]issues of stigma and discrimination
[normal] 
[normal]need to be addressed.  
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]5.4
[normal] 
[normal]Work
[normal]ing
[normal] with the individual to build confidence and 
[normal]rights
[normal]-awareness
[normal],
[normal] as well as work
[normal]ing
[normal] with the wider community to promote understanding and support is vital
[normal]. 
[normal]For example, in
[normal] the TLMEW-
[normal]supported 
[normal]M
[normal]IRANDA
[normal] project in Myanmar
[normal],
[normal] Disability Resource Centres are providing physiotherapy service
[normal]s
[normal] to people with disabilities, 
[normal]as well as
[normal] counselling an
[normal]d
[normal] rights-
[normal]awareness. They
[normal] have
[normal] 
[normal]established 
[normal]self-help groups w
[normal]h
[normal]ere people with disabilities provide support 
[normal]for
[normal] each other for
[normal] livelihood development and 
[normal]run
[normal] community awareness programmes on disability.  
[normal]These activities have resulted in p
[normal]eople with disabilities 
[normal]became more valued and
[normal] 
[normal]included in 
[normal]society
[normal] 
[normal]and 
[normal]the whole community has
[normal] benefited from more accessible raised pathways that are wheelchair accessible
[normal], meaning they
[normal] 
[normal]no longer have
[normal] to wade through 
[normal]monsoon floods
[normal] to get to 
[normal]the marketpla
[normal]ce
[normal] 
[normal](
[normal]See 
[normal]Annex 3)
