[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.1
[normal] 
[normal]Although it is essential to address the rights of persons with disabilities, it should be recognised that some people experience disability that could 
[normal]be
[normal] prevented. M
[normal]inimisation of the cau
[normal]ses of disability is paramount (see Annex 4).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.2
[normal] 
[normal]Neglected Tropical Diseases 
[normal](NTDs) 
[normal]such as 
[normal]Leprosy, Lymphatic 
[normal]Filariasis
[normal] and Trachoma 
[normal]are a significant cause of serious disability worldwide 
[normal]representing
[normal] high levels of Disability Adjusted Life Years (DALYS - the sum of the potential life lost due to pr
[normal]emature mortality and the years of productive life lost due to disability)
[normal]. These treatable diseases 
[normal]must be addressed in order to prevent people developing disabilities
[normal]. Thus,
[normal] DFID’s approach to NTDs should be li
[normal]nked to its disability strategy.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]6.3
[normal] 
[normal]A
[normal]ddressing NTDs is not just about mass drug administration. For many of those who have received late diagnosis and treatment
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]disability is already a result.
[normal] For some the disability is obvious. Others, including 
[normal]people
[normal] affected by leprosy
[normal], 
[normal]may not have a vi
[normal]sual disability
[normal] but like those with diabetes
[normal] the sensation loss they experience
[normal] is 
[normal]disabling
[normal].
[normal]  
[normal]P
[normal]roper self-care and management of their conditions is 
[normal]essential in preventing 
[normal]further disability.
[normal] 
[normal]A
[normal] disability i
[normal]s not always visible 
[normal]n
[normal]or obvious, yet 
[normal]n
[normal]ot 
[normal]supporting 
[normal]a person 
[normal]in
[normal] prevention of disability
[normal] 
[normal]can
[normal] lead to further 
[normal]impairment.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]7.1
[normal] 
[normal]Inequalities intersect
[normal],
[normal] so a person with 
[normal]a 
[normal]disability may also be marginalised in other ways such as gender, caste, 
[normal]ethnicity
[normal], living in
[normal] remote
[normal] locations
[normal] or by leprosy
[normal]-related
[normal] stigma
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]7.2
[normal] 
[normal]B
[normal]eing marginalised in one way 
[normal]often
[normal] leads to 
[normal]other forms of marginalisation
[normal]; for example poor access to health care due to discrimination due to ethnicity or caste may lead to late treatment 
[normal]after 
[normal]an accident 
[normal]or after contracting a disease
[normal],
[normal] resulting in disability.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]7.3
[normal] 
[normal]It is notable that the risk of disability occurring is heightene
[normal]d due to marginalisation
[normal],
[normal] and further marginalisation is more likely 
[normal]to occur
[normal] due to disability. 
[normal] [bold]This therefore leads to 
[normal]a 
[normal]bi
[normal]-
[normal]directional link to poverty: disability may increase the risk of poverty, and poverty may increase the risk of disability
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]DFID should:
[normal]8.1
[normal] 
[normal]Demonstrate[bold] best practice[bold] 
[normal]in inclusive development[bold] by 
[normal]building disability into [bold]its strategic frameworks[bold] and budgets[bold], and 
[normal]develop
[normal]ing
[normal] an 
[normal]equity and inclusion strategy [bold]that ensures 
[normal]a focus on disability inclusion. This should include 
[normal]assigning a senior staff member at DFID and a lead person responsible for disability inclusion in [bold]each country office[bold]. This person
[normal] would
[normal] have responsibility for championing and monitoring
[normal] disab
[normal]ility incl
[normal]usion, 
[normal]sharing good practice
[normal] and ensuring the implementation of Article 32 of the 
[normal]UNCRPD
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.2
[normal] 
[normal]T[bold]ake a leadership role in discussion[bold]s[bold] around the post-2015 development framework[bold], 
[normal]championing disability[bold] inclusion[bold] to ensure it is an integral part of any new development framework
[normal]. To maintain its commitment to the implementation of disability inclusive development
[normal] and to keep disability on the international agenda
[normal], DFID should 
[normal]make specific disability-related 
[normal]pledge
[normal]s in 2014 e.g. three
[normal] DFID country programmes to be fully inclusive be 2016, all DFID funded projects required to report on disability disaggregated data, etc.)
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]8.3
[normal] 
[normal]P[bold]romote the voice of disabled people[bold] in[bold] development processe[bold]s[bold], ensuring they are i
[normal]ncluded in strategy development, 
[normal]programme planning
[normal], monitoring and evaluation
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.4
[normal] 
[normal]M[bold]ake [bold]‘
[normal]Disability’ a core, cross[bold]-[bold]cutting element of all [bold]development [bold]programmes[bold],[bold] [bold]investing in good practice and recognising the benefits of[bold] a [bold]twin track approach.[bold] Guidance should recommend that
[normal] mainstream NGOs and G
[normal]overnment
[normal]s partner
[normal] 
[normal]with organisation
[normal]s
[normal] with expertise in 
[normal]disability, such as Disable
[normal]d
[normal] People’s Orga
[normal]nisations (DPOs) and disability-
